notesStmt.note: This is an illustrated and illuminated copy of the collection of poems (dīvān) by Shams al-Dīn Muḥammad Ḥāfiz al-Shīrāzī (fl. eighth century AH / fourteenth CE), produced in India, possibly Kashmir, in the thirteenth century AH / nineteenth CE. It opens with an illuminated headpiece with the doxological formula (basmalah) (fol. 1b); there are twenty illustrations. The lacquer binding with central floral design is contemporary with the manuscript.

msContents.textLang: The primary language in this manuscript is Persian.

layoutDesc.layout: Framing lines in blue, orange, gold, and black

decoDesc.decoNote: Twenty illustrations; illuminated headpiece; framing lines in blue, orange, gold, and black

decoNote.title: Binding
decoNote.note: This lacquer binding is decorated with a floral central design surrounded by a border of gold-painted floral motifs on a black ground. It dates to the thirteenth century AH / nineteenth CE.

decoNote.title: Incipit page with headpiece
decoNote.note: This painted incipit page has a headpiece inscribed with the doxological formula (basmalah).

decoNote.title: The Prophet Muhammad (not depicted) ascends on Burāq
King Solomon seated on his throne carried by demons
Laylá and Majnūn and Sultan Maḥmūd and Iyāz
decoNote.note: In the foreground of this illustration, Sultan Maḥmūd and his favorite, Iyāz, are shown. Behind are Laylá and Majnūn. All four are referred to in this ode.

decoNote.title: A wine party
Shīrīn before Farhād, who is cutting through rocks
Jamshīd and Kay Khusraw
King Solomon with his magic seal (signet) and a demon
Jamshīd and Kay Qubād
Alexander the Great and his magic mirror
decoNote.note: Ḥāfiẓ, like Iskandar (Alexander the Great), uses a mirror to seek his beloved.

decoNote.title: Kay Khusraw prefers the Water of Life to wine
Jacob becomes blind during his long wait without hearing anything from Joseph
Farhād carries Shīrīn and her dead horse to her castle
Shīrīn visits Farhād with her men
The beloved admired by Jamshīd and Kay Khusraw
decoNote.note: This page illustrates the first couplet on the page, in which the poet comments that his beloved has hundreds of Jamshīds and Kay Khusraws as slaves.

decoNote.title: Alexander the Great and the prophet Khiḍr
The crucifixion of Ḥallāj
King Solomon in the company of angels, demons, and flying birds
Paradise represented by a pavilion in a garden with water pools and angels
Sultan Maḥmūd and Iyāz
Jamshīd enthroned

binding.p: Lacquer binding (without flap); central panel filled with floral design; border with floral gold-painted motifs on a black ground
